window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>1","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPTS OF MATTER : CONCEPTS OF MATTER","question":"Which of the following physical processes cannot be explained by the molecular theory of matter?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Evaporation","B":"thermal conduction","C":"radiation of heat","D":"convention currents in fluids"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Radiation cannot be explained by the molecular theory of matter. It is the movement of electro-magnetic waves not matter (particles).","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>2","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"NEWTON\u2019S LAWS OF MOTION : SECOND LAW","question":"A spring balance, which is suspended from the roof of a lift, carries a mass of 1kg at its free end. if the lift accelerates upwards at 2.5ms-2, determines the reading on the spring balance. [g = 10ms-2]","images":[],"options":{"A":"25.0N","B":"12.5N","C":"7.5N","D":"4.0N"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Since the lift is accelerating upwards,  The total force will be,   F = Ma  \u21d2 1 \u00d7 2.5 = 2.5N  Weight = mg = 1 \u00d7 10 = 10N  Reading = F + wt = 2.5 + 10 = 12.5N","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>3","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"FLUID AT REST : EQUILIBRIUM OF BODIES: ARCHIMEDES\u2019 PRINCIPLE","question":"An object of weight 10N immersed in a liquid displaces a quantity of the liquid. if the liquid displaced weighs 6N. determine the upthrust on the object","images":[],"options":{"A":"20N","B":"10N","C":"6N","D":"4N"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The upthrust on an object immersed in a fluid is equal to the weight of the fluid displaced by the object. In this case, the weight of the liquid displaced is 6N, so the upthrust on the object is also 6N.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>4","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"FLUID AT REST : PRESSURE IN FLUIDS","question":"Which of the following statement about pressure is not correct? pressure","images":[],"options":{"A":"increases with an increase in surface area","B":"decreases with an increase in surface area","C":"increases with a decrease in surface area","D":"increases with an increase in the applied force"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Pressure is defined as the force per unit area. Therefore, if the surface area increases while the force remains constant, the pressure decreases. This is because the force is spread over a larger area, reducing the pressure. Hence, the statement 'pressure increases with an increase in surface area' is not correct.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>5","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"FLUID AT REST : EQUILIBRIUM OF BODIES: ARCHIMEDES\u2019 PRINCIPLE","question":"The apparent weight of a body fully immersed in water is 32N and its weight in air is 96N. calculate the volume of the body.[Density of water = 1000kg m3, g = 10ms-2]","images":[],"options":{"A":"8.9 \u00d710-3m3","B":"6.4 \u00d710-3m3","C":"3.2 \u00d710-3m3","D":"3.0 \u00d710-3m3"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When fully immersed in water,  apparent weight = 32N   Weight in air = 96N  Therefore, the upthrust = weight in Air - weight in water  \u21d2 96 - 32 = 64N  Also, F = Ma  Therefore, M=Fa=Fg=6410=6.4kg  DensityMassvolume,Volume=Massdensity  =6.41000=6.4\u00d710-3m3","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>6","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"MOTION : SOLID FRICTION","question":"A block weighing 15N rest on a flat surface and a horizontal force of 3N is exerted on it. Determine the frictional force on the block.","images":[],"options":{"A":"0.3N","B":"0.5N","C":"3.0N","D":"5.0N"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Weight = Force of gravity = 15N  Applied force = 3N  The block is not accelerating,  Therefore the block is in it's static state,  F = UF  Also, U = Applied Force/Weight  U=315=0.2  Therefore,  where F is the normal force  U is the coefficient of friction  F is the weight  F = 0.2 \u00d7 15 = 3N","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>7","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"MOTION : CAUSE OF MOTION","question":"Which of the following equation represents the distance x, travelled by a body moving on a straight road with a constant speed ? [The other symbols have their usual meaning]","images":[],"options":{"A":"X = ut + 1/2at2","B":"X = ut","C":"x=V2-u22a","D":"X = - 1/2 at2"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The equation for distance travelled by a body moving with a constant speed is given by X = ut, where 'u' is the initial velocity and 't' is the time. The other equations involve acceleration (a), which is not present in a motion with constant speed.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>8","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : ENERGY OF S.H.M","question":"The amplitude of the motion of a body performing simple harmonic decreases with time because","images":[],"options":{"A":"frictional forces dissipate the energy with time","B":"The frequency of oscillation varies with time","C":"the period of oscillation varies over time","D":"energy is supplied by some external agencies"},"answer":"A","explanation":"In a simple harmonic motion, the amplitude decreases with time due to the dissipation of energy by frictional forces. The frequency and period of oscillation do not vary with time in simple harmonic motion, and energy is not supplied by external agencies.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>9","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : SPEED AND ACCELERATION OF S.H.M","question":"The amplitude of the particle executing simple harmonic motion is 5cm while it angular frequency is 10 rads-1.calculate the magnitude of the maximum acceleration of the particle.","images":[],"options":{"A":"0.25ms-1","B":"0.50ms-1","C":"2.00ms-1","D":"5.00ms-1"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Maximum acceleration (a) = w2r  w = 10, r = 5cm = 0.05m  substituting values for w and r, we have   a = 102 \u00d7 0.05 = 5ms-2","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>10","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"NEWTON\u2019S LAWS OF MOTION : SECOND LAW","question":"The time rates of change of momentum is","images":[],"options":{"A":"impulse","B":"force","C":"power","D":"pressure"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The tie rate of change of momentum is force.  This is gotten from Newton's second law.  The rate of change of linear momentum of a body is directly proportional to the external force applied on the body, and takes place always in the direction of the force applied.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>11","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPTS OF MATTER : CONCEPTS OF MATTER","question":"Which of the following statement about elastic collision is correct ?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Momentum is lost due to the sound produced","B":"loss in momentum is equal to loss in kinetic energy","C":"Both kinetic energy and momentum are conserved","D":"kinetic energy is lost while momentum is conserved"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In an elastic collision, both momentum and kinetic energy are conserved. This means that the total momentum and total kinetic energy before the collision is equal to the total momentum and total kinetic energy after the collision.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>12","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC ENERGY AND POWER","question":"Electrical resistance is a property of an electrical conductor that causes electrical energy to be converted into","images":[],"options":{"A":"mechanical energy","B":"heat energy","C":"magnetic energy","D":"chemical energy"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Electrical resistance is a property of an electrical conductor that opposes the flow of an electric current resulting in the conversion of electrical energy into heat energy. This is due to the collisions of the moving particles within the conductor which generates heat.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>13","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"MACHINES :","question":"A simple machine with an efficiency of 75% lifts a load of 5000 N when a force of 500N is applied to it. calculate the velocity ratio of the machine","images":[],"options":{"A":"10.0","B":"13.3","C":"17.5","D":"25.0"},"answer":"B","explanation":"M.A=LoadEffort  Load = 5000N, Effort = 500N  M.A=5000N500N=10    Efficiency=M.AV.R=0.75  V.R=M.AEfficiency=100.75=13.3","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>14","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"MACHINES :","question":"A screw jack with a tommy bar of length 12cm is used to raise a car through a vertical height of 25cm by turning the Tommy bar through 50 revolutions. Calculate the approximate velocity ratio of the jack.[\u03c0 = 3.14]","images":[],"options":{"A":"21","B":"38","C":"48","D":"151"},"answer":"D","explanation":"V.R=2\u03c0ap  a=12,p=2550=0.5  substituting values  V.R=2 \u00d7 3.14\u00d7120.5=151","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>15","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"A beam PQ pivoted at P carries a load of 80N as shown above . calculate the effort, E, required to keep it horizontal. [Neglect the weight of the beam]","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"32.0N","B":"26.7N","C":"16.0N","D":"13.3N"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Clock-wise motion = Anti-clockwise motion  substituting values,  3 \u00d7 E = 80 \u00d7 0.5  3E = 40  E=403=13.3N","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>16","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : TEMPERATURE AND ITS MEASUREMENT","question":"A resistance thermometer has a resistance of 20\u03a9 at 100\u2218C. if the resistance is 52\u03a9 in a medium . calculate the corresponding temperature.","images":[],"options":{"A":"49.2\u2218C","B":"60.6\u2218C","C":"80.0\u2218C","D":"84.7\u2218C"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Therefore, 100 - 0x - 0=85 - 2052 - 20  X=100 \u00d7 3265 = 49.2\u00b0C","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>17","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : GAS LAWS","question":"A given mass of an ideal gas has a pressure of 500N m-2 at -13\u2218C. if its volume remains constant, calculate its pressure at 247\u2218C.","images":[],"options":{"A":"25N m-2","B":"50N m-2","C":"500N m-2","D":"1000N m-2"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Volume is constant  From the question,  P1 = 500Nm-2, T1 = -13\u00b0C = 260K, P2 = ?, T2 = 247\u00b0C  T2 = 247\u00b0C + 273\u00b0C = 520K    Using pressure law,  P1T1=P2T2  P2=P1T2T1  substituting  P2=500\u00d7520260=1000Nm-2","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>18","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : GAS LAWS","question":"The volume of an ideal gas has a pressure of 77cm Hg and temperature 60\u2218C is 240cm3. if the temperature and pressure are increased at 98\u2218C and 81 Hg respectively. calculate the new volume of the gas .","images":[],"options":{"A":"411.5 cm3","B":"267.1cm3","C":"254.2cm3","D":"112.7cm3"},"answer":"C","explanation":"V1P1T1=V2P2T2  V1 = 240cm3  P1 = 77mmHg  T1 = 60\u00b0C = 60 + 273 = 333K  V2 = ?, P2 = 81mmHg, T2 = 98\u00b0C = 98 + 273 = 371K  V2=V1P1T2T1P2  =240 x 77 x 371333 x 81 = 254.2cm3","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>19","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : LATENT HEAT","question":"The amount of heat given out or absorbed whe a substance changes its state at a constant temperature is known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"latent heat","B":"heat capacity","C":"specific latent heat","D":"specific heat capacity"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Latent Heat is the heat required to convert a solid into a liquid or vapour, or a liquid to vapour, without change in temperature.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>20","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : VAPOUR AND VAPOUR PRESSURE","question":"Which of the following physical quantities affects the saturated vapour pressure of the liquid","images":[],"options":{"A":"Temperature","B":"volume","C":"mass","D":"Density"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The saturated vapour pressure of a liquid is the pressure exerted by a vapour in thermodynamic equilibrium with its condensed phases at a given temperature. It is dependent on the temperature of the liquid. As the temperature increases, the kinetic energy of the molecules increases, and more molecules can escape from the surface of the liquid to the vapour phase, increasing the saturated vapour pressure.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>21","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : HUMIDITY AND THE WEATHER","question":"Humidity is used to describe the amount of","images":[],"options":{"A":"air in water vapour","B":"cloud available in the atmosphere","C":"air in equal colume of cloud","D":"water vapour in the atomsphere"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Humidity is a measure of the amount of water vapour in the atmosphere. It is not a measure of the amount of air in water vapour, the amount of cloud available in the atmosphere, or the amount of air in an equal volume of cloud. Therefore, the correct answer is 'water vapour in the atmosphere'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>22","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"PROPERTIES OF WAVES : REFRACTION","question":"Surface waves travelling in deep water at 15ms-1 are incident at shallow water boundary. if the angles of incidence and refraction are 45\u2218 and 30\u2218 respectively, calculate the speed of the waves in shallow waters.","images":[],"options":{"A":"8.7 cm","B":"10.6 cm","C":"15.4 cm","D":"17 cm"},"answer":"B","explanation":"index(n)=sin isin r=speed in deep waterspeed in shallow water  subsituting values,  sin 45sin 30=15x  x=15sin30sin45=10.6ms-1","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>23","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : PLANE MIRROR","question":"An incident ray is reflected normally by a plane mirror onto a screen where it forms a bright spot. the mirror and screen are parallel and 1m apart.if the mirror is rotated through 5\u2218 calculate the displacement. of the spot.","images":[],"options":{"A":"8.7cm","B":"10.0cm","C":"15.4cm","D":"17.6cm"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Angle of rotation = 5\u00b0  Glancing angle = 2 \u00d7 angle of rotation  \u21d2 2 \u00d7 5\u00b0 = 10\u00b0  tan\u03b8=Displacement from spotOriginal distance  tan10=x100cm  x = 100tan10 = 100 \u00d7 0.176 = 17.6cm","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>24","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : APPLICATION OF LENSES IN OPTICAL INSTRUMENTS","question":"Convex spherical mirrors are preferred to plane mirrors as driving mirrors because","images":[],"options":{"A":"the image produced are upright and clearly visible","B":"it provides a wider field of view","C":"the image produced is erect and diminished","D":"the image produced is not laterally inverted."},"answer":"B","explanation":"Convex spherical mirror gives a wider view, which allow the driver see most of the traffic behind him.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>25","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"An object is placed 260 cm from a lens . calculate the magnification of the  image","images":[],"options":{"A":"28","B":"26","C":"24","D":"13"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Magnification=VirtualReal=VU  =26020=13","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>26","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : SOURCES OF LIGHT","question":"A piece of cloth appears green in sunlight. when held in red light, it appears","images":[],"options":{"A":"green","B":"blue","C":"red","D":"black"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A piece of green cloth held under a red light will appear black, this is because the green colour is absorbed by the red spectrum, no colour is reflected, hence the black colour.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>27","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : DISPERSION OF WHITE LIGHT","question":"Dispersion of white light by a glass prism occurs because","images":[],"options":{"A":"A white light consists of a mixture of seven different colours","B":"Refractive index of glass is different for each constituent for each colour","C":"The speed of each colour of light in for each colour","D":"speed of each colour of light in the glass is proportional to the angle of refractive index of glass"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Dispersion of white light by a glass prism occurs because the refractive index of glass is different for each constituent color. This is due to a phenomenon known as dispersion, where different wavelengths (or colors) of light are refracted by different amounts. This causes the white light to split into its constituent colors, creating a spectrum.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>28","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"SOUND WAVES : TRANSMISSION OF SOUND WAVES","question":"Which of the following statement about sound is correct?","images":[],"options":{"A":"A sound wave travels for the normal at point of incidence","B":"sound travel faster in air than water","C":"the wavelength of sound changes when its travels from air to  water","D":"the frequency of sound changes when it travels from air to water"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The correct statement about sound is that the wavelength of sound changes when it travels from air to water. This is because the speed of sound is different in different mediums. When sound travels from air to water, its speed increases, and since the frequency remains the same (as frequency is a property of the source and doesn't change with medium), the wavelength must increase (since speed = frequency x wavelength).","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>29","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"SOUND WAVES : VIBRATION IN STRINGS","question":"The diagram above shows the wire of a sonometer box set into resonance by vibrating turning fork of frequency, f, when the wire is stretched by a tension T, the resonating length of the sound produced is \u22cb         Which of the following statement is not correct? The wave produced on the wire is","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"stationary and longitudinal","B":"stationary and mechanical","C":"mechanical and longitudinal","D":"progressive and transverse"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Sound wave are longitudinal and since , it is a standing wave, it is stationary","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>30","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"SOUND WAVES : VIBRATION IN STRINGS","question":"The diagram above shows the wire of a sonometer box set into resonance by vibrating turning fork of frequency, f, when the wire is stretched by a tension T, the resonating length of the sound produced is \u22cb       Which of the following statement about the frequency of mass per unit is not correct? it is","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"proportional to the mass per unit length of the wire","B":"Equal to the frequency of the turning fork","C":"inversely proportional to the lenght of the wire","D":"proportional to the  square root of the tension"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The frequency of vibration of a wire is not proportional to the mass per unit length of the wire.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>31","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"SOUND WAVES : VIBRATION IN STRINGS","question":"The diagram above shows the wire of a sonometer box set into resonance by vibrating turning fork of frequency, f, when the wire is stretched by a tension T, the resonating length of the sound produced is \u22cb       if the frequency of the turning fork at resonance is 256Hz, calculate the frequency of vibration of the wire when the tension in the wire is increased to 196N.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"130.6Hz","B":"182.9Hz","C":"358.4Hz","D":"501.8Hz"},"answer":"C","explanation":"F = k&radic;T&nbsp;  From this relationship we know,  F1&radic;T1&nbsp;=F2&radic;T2&nbsp;  From question  T1 = 100N, T2 = 196N, F1 = 256Hz, F2 = ?   Making F2 the subject of formular  F2=F1&radic;T2&nbsp;&radic;T1&nbsp;=256&radic;196&nbsp;10  F2 = 358.4Hz","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>32","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"GRAVITATIONAL FIELD : NEWTON\u2019S LAW OF GRAVITATION","question":"The magnitude of the gravitational force between two particles 0.10m apart is 10N. if the distance between them is increased to 0.20m, calculate the magnitude of the new force","images":[],"options":{"A":"40.0N","B":"20.0N","C":"5.0N","D":"2.5N"},"answer":"D","explanation":"F=kr2  Therefore,  F1r12 = F2r22  F1 = 10N, r1 = 0.10m, F2 = ?, r2 = 0.2  making F2 the subject,  F2=&radic;F1r12&nbsp;r22=10(0.1)2(0.2)2=2.5N","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>33","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CAPACITANCE, ARRANGEMENT AND APPLICATION","question":"As plates of a charged variable capacitors are moved closer together, the potential difference between them","images":[],"options":{"A":"increases","B":"decreases","C":"remains the same","D":"is doubled"},"answer":"B","explanation":"As the distance between the plates decreases, capacitance increases. And as capacitance increases, the potential difference decreases since potential difference is inversely proportional to the capacitance so that the charge remains constant (V = Q/C)","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>34","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CAPACITANCE, ARRANGEMENT AND APPLICATION","question":"Use the diagram to answer  question       What is the effective capacitance in the circuit?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"2 \u00b5F","B":"6 \u00b5F","C":"18 \u00b5F","D":"216 \u00b5F"},"answer":"A","explanation":"For capacitors in series  1C1+1C2+1C3+1C4...  Therefore,  1C1+1C2+1C3  16+16+16=36=12  C = 2 \u00b5F","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>35","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC ENERGY AND POWER","question":"Use the diagram to answer  question   What is the total energy stored by the capacitors?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"2.0 \u00d710-4 J","B":"1.0\u00d710-4 J","C":"9.0\u00d710-4 J","D":"1.0\u00d710-2 J"},"answer":"D","explanation":"TotalEnergy=E=12CV2  E=12CV2  substituting values,  E=12\u00d72\u00d710-6\u00d7104J=10-2J","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>36","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"Three identical lamps each of power 100w, are connected in a parallel across a potential difference of 250v. calculate the current in the circuit","images":[],"options":{"A":"7.5A","B":"2.5A","C":"1.2A","D":"0.8A"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Power = IV  making I the subject of the formula  I = P/V  Eachlamphascurrent,I=100250=25A  Potential difference across equals = I1 + I2 + I3  =25+25+25=1.2Amperes","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>37","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC ENERGY AND POWER","question":"An electric bulb is rated 60W, 220V. calculate the resistance of its filament when it is operating normally","images":[],"options":{"A":"296.7\u03a9","B":"400.0\u03a9","C":"512.2\u03a9","D":"806.7\u03a9"},"answer":"D","explanation":"P=V2R  where,  P = Power, V = Potential difference, R = Resistance  Making R the subject of formular   R = V2/P = (220)2/60 = 806.7\u03a9","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>38","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"MAGNETIC FIELD : THE EARTH\u2019S MAGNETIC FIELD","question":"The earth 's magnetic equator passes through jos in Nigeria at jos, the","images":[],"options":{"A":"angle of variation is zero","B":"magnetic declination is 90\u2218.","C":"angle of dip is zero","D":"horizontal component of the earth's magnetic field is zero"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Jos, Nigeria is closer to the equator. The angle of dip at the equator is typically close to zero degrees. This means that the magnetic field lines are nearly horizontal to the Earth's surface.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>39","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"MAGNETIC FIELD : CONCEPT OF MAGNETIC FIELD","question":"Which of the following statement about magnetic lines of force is not correct?","images":[],"options":{"A":"A magnetic line of force is an imaginary line which the north pole of a magnet would describe if it is free to move","B":"magnetic lines of force do not cross one another","C":"The presence of magnetic lines of force ina region indicates the presence of a manetic field","D":"magnetic lines of force are closely-packed together at neutral point"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A neutral point in a magnetic field is a point at which the horizontal component of earth's magnetic field and magnetic field due to the magnet are equal and opposite.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>40","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"MAGNETIC FIELD : USE OF ELECTROMAGNETS","question":"The material used for reconstructing the core of an electromagnet is","images":[],"options":{"A":"iron","B":"carbon","C":"copper","D":"steel"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The core of an electromagnet is usually made from a ferromagnetic material like iron. This is because iron has a high magnetic permeability, meaning it can easily be magnetized and demagnetized. This property makes it ideal for use in the core of an electromagnet.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>41","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"SIMPLE A.C. CIRCUITS : RESONANCE","question":"In a circuit diagram above calculate the energy stored in the inductor at resonance","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"0.100J","B":"0.050J","C":"0.010J","D":"0.005J"},"answer":"B","explanation":"At resonance,  I=VR  100100=1Ampere  Energystoredininductor=12L12  substituting,  L=12(0.1)(1)2 = 0.05J","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>42","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"SIMPLE A.C. CIRCUITS : REACTANCE AND IMPEDANCE","question":"calculate the reactance of the inductor in the circuit diagram shown above.[\u22bc = 22/7]","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"132\u03a9","B":"214\u03a9","C":"264\u03a9","D":"269\u03a9"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Resistance of inductor = XL = 2\u03c0fL  2x227x60x0.71=264\u03a9","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>43","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : ENERGY QUANTIZATION","question":"In which of the following transitions is the largest quantum of energy liberated by an hydrogen atom when the electron changes energy levels? (n is the quantum number )","images":[],"options":{"A":"n = 2 to n = 1","B":"n = 1 to n = 2","C":"n = 2 to n = 3","D":"n = 3 to n= 2"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The energy difference between energy levels in a hydrogen atom is given by the Rydberg formula. The energy difference is greatest when the transition is from n=2 to n=1. This is because the energy levels in a hydrogen atom are not equally spaced, but get closer together as n increases. Therefore, the energy difference is greatest for transitions to the n=1 level.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>44","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : ENERGY QUANTIZATION","question":"A photon of wavelength \u22cb\u2218 is emitted when an electron in an atom makes a transition from a level of energy 2Ek to that of energy Ek. if the electron transits from 4/3Ek to Ek level determine the wavelength of the proton that would be emitted","images":[],"options":{"A":"3\u22cb\u2218","B":"2\u22cb\u2218","C":"3/4\u22cb\u2218","D":"1/3\u22cb\u2218"},"answer":"D","explanation":"2EK - EK = \u22cb0  EK = \u22cb0  43EK-EK=x  =4EK - 3EK3=x  EK3=0  but EK = \u22cb0  substituting,  x=\u22cb03=13\u22cb","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>45","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : X-RAYS","question":"Production of x-ray in an x-ray tubes begins with","images":[],"options":{"A":"photo electric emission","B":"collision of electrons","C":"thermionic emission","D":"field  emission of electrons"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The production of X-rays in an X-ray tube begins with thermionic emission. In this process, electrons are emitted from a heated filament. These electrons are then accelerated towards a metal target, producing X-rays when they collide with the target atoms.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>46","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : COMPOSITION OF THE NUCLEUS","question":"The nucleon number and the proton number of a neutral atom of an element are 23 and 11 respectively. how many neutrons are present in the atom?","images":[],"options":{"A":"11","B":"12","C":"23","D":"34"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The nucleon number of an atom is the total number of protons and neutrons in the nucleus. Given that the nucleon number is 23 and the proton number is 11, the number of neutrons can be calculated by subtracting the proton number from the nucleon number. Therefore, the number of neutrons is 23 - 11 = 12.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>47","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : FUSION AND FISSION","question":"A nitrogen nucleus bombarded with alpha particles produces an oxygen nucleus and proton. The nuclear reaction for this process is 42He + 148N \u2192178O + 11 + Q. Which of the following statement about the reaction is not correct?","images":[],"options":{"A":"A bombardment result into a nucleus with a greater proton number","B":"it is an induced nuclear reaction greater proton number","C":"it is a natural radioactive decay","D":"the sum of the initial nucleon numbers is equal to the sum of final nucleon numbers"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The given nuclear reaction is an example of induced nuclear reaction, not a natural radioactive decay. In natural radioactive decay, the nucleus of an atom spontaneously disintegrates into a different nucleus or different particle. However, in this case, the nitrogen nucleus is bombarded with alpha particles to produce an oxygen nucleus and a proton, which is a process of induced nuclear reaction.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>48","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"ENERGY : WORLD ENERGY RESOURCES","question":"In nuclear reactor, electricity can be generated through the following processes, arrange the process in the correct order  I. The steam is used to drive turbines   II. The heat energy released is removed by passing water through the reactor   III. The turbines in turn generates electricity  IV. The water then passes through some form of heat exchanger to produce steam","images":[],"options":{"A":"II,IV,I and III","B":"I,II,III and IV","C":"III,I,IV and II","D":"IV,I,III and II"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The heat energy is released is removed by passing water through the reactor, which produces steam, the steam drives the turbine which produces electricity.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>49","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"WAVE-PARTICLE PARADOX : DUALITY OF MATTER","question":"Electrons passing through crystals are diffracted because they","images":[],"options":{"A":"Are repelled by the atoms in the crystal","B":"Are attracted by the atoms in the crystal","C":"posses wave properties","D":"are particles"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Electrons passing through crystals are diffracted because they possess wave properties. This is based on the wave-particle duality principle in quantum mechanics, which states that every particle or quantum entity can be described as both a particle and a wave.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2001>50","subject":"Physics","year":"2001","type":"Objective","topic":"WAVE-PARTICLE PARADOX : DUALITY OF MATTER","question":"The duality of matter implies that","images":[],"options":{"A":"exits as a particle of dual composition","B":"has momentum and energy","C":"has both wave and particles properties","D":"is made of dual materials"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Matter exhibit both wave and particle properties. It is the concept of quantum mechanics that every particle can be described as a \"wave\" or \"particle\".","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"}];